  "response": "There are several significant legal precedents related to money laundering cases, including landmark decisions and key statutes:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- First major U.S. legislation addressing financial reporting requirements\n- Established reporting standards for financial transactions\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal offense\n- Expanded legal framework for prosecuting financial crimes\n\n3. Notable Supreme Court Cases:\n- United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Defended interpretation of money laundering statutes\n- Clarified legal definitions of financial transactions\n\n4. International Precedents:\n- Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Established international anti-money laundering standards\n\n5. Significant Prosecution Cases:\n- HSBC money laundering settlement (2012)\n- Bernie Madoff Ponzi scheme prosecution\n- Demonstrated enforcement of complex financial regulations\n\nThese precedents have shaped modern legal approaches to combating financial crimes, establishing frameworks for investigation, prosecution, and prevention of money laundering activities.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legal precedents?",
